segments.text: I suppose it was true to the kind of thinking that was prevalent in the early planning movement in the country, and in El Paso as well, that some of the elements of the Kessler plan had to do with aesthetics as much as anything else.

Some of the thinking in the plan regarding submerging the railroad tracks that cross the center of the city, which had a functional merit in terms of improving traffic through the downtown and had an aesthetic
benefit in cleaning up that section of the city.
These kinds of things were incorporated in there.
For the period in which it was done, it was probably a wise and a very useful plan.
Together with that plan, the initial basic structure of the planning within the city was established with the appointment of a plan commission.
The city still retains that name.
We have a city plan commission as though we had still that one plan that we were following.
I suppose as a shortcoming to that plan and to the early planning thinking, there was less thought given to the overall traffic and transportation layout within the developing areas of the city.
And the city went for some time without really
good articulation of a circulation pattern.
Furthermore, some of the growth areas of the city were not well thought out in terms of how they would relate to the inner core of the city.
The Kessler plan spoke very much to the developed area of the community and tried to enhance the livability of aspects of the city as it existed then.
The growth which followed, particularly as the city entered that very accelerated growth curve in the 50s, initially began to move without a lot of good local planning thinking.
There was borrowing from some of the kind of subdivision design and such that was
available and known from other communities, but it had no signature saying this is the way El Paso should develop.
It certainly was not being guided by the central management of the city government.
I think probably the most significant thing that happened during the period of the 50s and early 60s was the beginning of the articulation of a circulation pattern within the community.
The designation of certain streets as major thoroughfares, the planned extension of them,
the incorporation of standards regarding useful and necessary right-of-way widths and paving widths.
As a shortcoming to that thinking, all those standards could be listed in plans and plan documents.
I think although there was a lot of contribution made to the city's development in the way of

The thinking on the transportation system and the street network, you could criticize that whole period as to say that due to politics, due to funding limitations, due to inability to coordinate development among different governmental jurisdictions, notably the city and the school district, many things kind of went their own way.
There was not a good program to acquire park
park sites.
There was not development of a good neighborhood concept with the relationship of a school and park space and residential areas.
There were many shortcomings and probably during the period of the post-war growth boom began, a long certain
highways that served at that time as the almost sole transportation route.

The inevitable development of strip commercial uses, the strip commercial pattern that today, I realize this is practically true to any city, but it always seems terribly unfortunate, the hodgepodge pattern of
commercial uses on small lots and their signs.

It speaks very poorly of a city's image of itself and it perhaps would be a valid criticism of the thinking during that period that the body politic didn't see reason to try to arrest the ugliest parts of those developments and create a more pleasing community image that would be evidence from traveling along those highways.
This was the immediate post-World War II era.
Immediate post-World War II era that saw doubling the population of the city and some of the most land extensive development that the community had ever seen at that time.
And then when the street pattern became involved with the interstate system.
The interstate system surely has to be this and any other community, I'm sure.
It has, it changed
It changed everything.

Carving up neighborhoods, defining new transportation routes, creating intersections of importance and enabling the city to grow in directions that never had done so before because of the increase in travel time.

When we look at planning in any community, we have to think of the decisions made by those transportation types that lay out interstate highways and decide where the interchanges will be and realize that their decisions have probably more long-reaching implications than much of what's done by what we term the real planners.
It's more, I guess, the planners have to understand and fully realize the implications of such things

All too often, I suppose no one really does, at least during that period, as the interstate system began to be implemented in the late 50s, that the far-reaching implications of it were not fully thought out.
Although I don't think the city suffers so much from that.
The interstate system in particular opened up the east side of El Paso, the upper escarpment, a very flat desert mesa that overlooks part of the Rio Grande Valley.
It opened it up, and today it still continues to outstrip the rest of the community in its growth.
Because of its more recent development, it does have a relatively well-articulated street network arterial pattern.
As I noted earlier, it has rather dearth of open space.
In many ways, I suppose it looks like every other community.
There still is not a true southwestern or El Paso signature on that development, as there could have been.
Going back for a minute to the Kessler plan, Mike, my reading of it surprised me because he doesn't talk about land use patterns.
No, he doesn't.
No, he doesn't.
It's circulation, including the railroad and parks
and so forth, but in terms of basic land use patterns, it's absent.
No, it's rather unfortunate that even when the city first established zoning ordinances and such, there didn't seem to be a lot of very weighty thinking given to land use patterns.
The initial charge, which was given to the city planning commission, which was created shortly after the Kessler plan was created, spoke almost exclusively of overseeing public investment.
the capital improvements the community would make, and to assure that they fit within the plan.
And it doesn't really speak to the role of the commission as a body recommending to the elected leaders changes in the pattern of the community's development from a land use perspective.
And that was probably the vacuum which created development patterns which we now look back at and use terms like blighted and such because it
It wasn't properly controlled in that period.
One thing I wanted to ask you about particularly is the work that you did when you were in the planning department on the Secundo Barrio.
South El Paso, I'm sure some of the other interviewees have talked about the planning that was done during the Chamazal boundary relocation.
It's just been mentioned, but not in any detail.
It might serve as an introduction to the South El Paso problem.
The Rio Grande River forms the international boundary.
By the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo, it is the boundary between the United States and Mexico.
It follows the center line of the river.

As the river changes and shifts course, the boundary moves with it with two provisions, whether that change is created by accretion, the slow movement and change of the river channel, or whether it's created by a sudden shift, in which case the boundary remains unchanged.
And it appears that in the 1860s, more or less, there was a flood that
through avulsion, that sudden change or shift of the river's course should have changed the international boundary.
However, the United States failed to acknowledge it.
It remained at a sore point between the United States and Mexico for many years until the Kennedy administration, when the administration chose to try to address that problem.
It became a rather unique situation in first physically relocating the river
second massive acquisition of properties on the US side to then be ceded to Mexico.

And in the course of that, although there was, I suppose, I don't remember the numbers exactly, I think approximately 450 acres of land in the United States was ceded to Mexico and another 250 to 300 acres from Mexico became part of the United States.
This was in the very center core of the city, an area that land values and development patterns were very intense.

There was an opportunity on the part of the United States to make use of the land acquired to create some, a number of things were done, improvements in the transportation pattern through the beginning of the first leg of a highway paralleling the river.
The acquisition of open space that today is the Chalmazal Memorial and the site of many important community events in the way of festivals for one thing or another and drama theaters and such.
The improvement bringing up to standard the relocation of a high school that was in a very crowded congested site that offered little in the way of outdoor play area and

It today is fully compatible with any of the newest high schools in the city in terms of its quality, in terms of the amount of space that's devoted to it, splinters of land that became available for public housing.
A number of different things were done there on the land acquired from Mexico on the U.S. side that was good and notable.
On the land that was ceded to Mexico, however, there was massive relocation necessary, the relocation of literally thousands of people.
This is...
The land that was involved in this immediately parallels the border.
Historically, it's been the site of housing for some of the poorest residents of the city, persons who have Hispanic heritage, persons who still have ties, family ties and economic ties with Mexico.
Although stereotypes are always dangerous, it could be stereotyped to say that certain neighborhoods within there represent, in essence,
first generation of the newer immigrants, particularly from Mexico.

These are persons who had the ambition to come across, whose skills and education limits them in terms of their economic ability, but they retain many of the kind of attitudes of what a neighborhood should be from their Mexican heritage, and it tends to be
very close-knit neighborhoods with intricate social organization, people whose associations are determined based on who lives in the next three blocks.
From a sociological perspective, this probably are the only two neighborhoods in El Paso that people really tend to interrelate as a sociologist believes they should.
Well, it was right in this area that mass relocation was necessary.

There were things done during that period that, at the insistence of John Cunningham, the then city planning director, that assistance be provided beyond the basic minimum compensation that the constitutional mandate would give for persons who had to be displaced, particularly those renters, to ensure that we didn't take a man of limited means and suddenly throw his life
you know, totally out of whack and do more harm than anything else to the individual.
In any case, this relocation was accomplished in a relatively short period.
And what followed then was a very sharply defined border along the area that
between the downtowns of El Paso and Juarez, there remained this neighborhood that is just generally referred to as South El Paso, or sometimes Segundo Barrio, Segundo meaning second.
It was the second ward back when the city in its early days had five voting wards, barrio being a Spanish term for neighborhood.
The housing patterns in there that had not been touched by the
channel relocation of the river, were some of the most intensively developed and populated sections of the city.
Tenements remained there from that period I spoke of earlier when the Mexican Revolution was going on and there was a massive influx of citizens.
Tenement buildings that offered two rooms and no indoor plumbing, typically two-story brick buildings.
that very tightly spaced together.
I suppose all in all, in that half square mile of the community that's called South El Paso, there was a population of roughly 25,000 people.
And that density may not seem... To understand that density, you also have to understand that you'd seldom find a building over two stories anywhere in that area.
This was a case of people packed together
not only on the land, but within the physical confines, the rooms they lived in, the rooms of their dwelling units and everything else.
Everything was very tightly packed.
In the early 70s, spurred on in part by a change in some federal programs, there was a move on the part of the city to address the housing problem in there.
the particular change in the programs I speak of, the public housing, which the city initially had several public housing units built.
There had been very little new public housing built in the city for some years.

The mandate from the Department of Housing and Urban Development was that the city would have to adopt a housing code, number one, and have to adopt it in a real sense by having a workable program for such code enforcement.
to arrest the blight and substandard housing conditions that existed.
Who took the leadership role in providing public housing in El Paso, would you say?
I couldn't honestly say.
Where did that begin?
What was the pressure for it?

I couldn't honestly say whether it came from the administration or within the planning department or within the housing authority which had been in existence now for almost 15, 20 years and exactly where the pressure came to diligently go after the funds that were available for new public housing.
I know that part of the
El Paso's never had a redevelopment agency.
No, the Urban Renewal Authority has been put before the citizens on three different occasions and suddenly defeated on three different times.
And yet it's had a housing authority for quite a while.
It had its earliest housing unit, I think, traces to 1948.
Again, I can't really answer your question where that
initial impetus to pursue the public funds available for where new housing came from.
But I do know that the charge then to make it work fell onto city staff, two departments, notably the public inspection department and the city planning department.

It was determined, a policy decision, it was determined that that code enforcement would be concentrated in south El Paso, the area that was known and acknowledged to have the worst housing conditions in the city.
Kessler noted that in his plan as well.
It's been around the city for a long time.
And it still exists.
It still is a problem in that area.
The attitude of the public inspection department was to make an inventory of the housing stock in there and select the worst housing units for demolition.
And this was somewhat at odds with the thinking of the city planning staff who thought it better to

Since if you simply want to categorize what does not meet code, 80% of all the structures down there would be outside of not in code compliance, but rather to concentrate in given areas where the land that would be made available for new development based on the demolition then could constitute big enough parcel sizes to allow for useful redevelopment.
The city planners didn't win out on that.
The code enforcement people did.
I do not know the numbers right off hand.
There were a number of these housing units, these tenements, which were destroyed.
There are people relocated into public housing, which, in keeping with the thinking of the day, was trying not to concentrate persons through public policy and assisted housing.
These housing units were scattered across the city.
There were a number of things the planners at the time were rather upset about, but the pressures were all coming from somewhere else.
The public housing officials, the code enforcement people, as I said, wanted to target what they considered to be the worst housing units.
It created a pattern like a pox across the neighborhood where lots sometimes as little as 25 feet wide and 125 feet long.
became available.
They were vacant, but they were still built up on either side.
There was really no opportunity for a redevelopment based on these parcel sizes that were being made available.
The relocation patterns of the residents, there was really no thinking about what was going on there in the way of

taking a very intricate social network that existed in that neighborhood, a true sociological neighborhood, as I pointed out earlier, and trying to preserve that intact, where persons with social ties would be relocated to areas that would enable them to maintain those social ties, or relocated as groups.
Rather, this was in keeping with national standards.
The elderly were put in elderly housing, and families were put in family housing,
And it began to destroy part of what the Hispanic neighborhood, which was more of a mixture of different age groups.
With their particular institutions.
Exactly.
And in some cases, these public housing units which were created in here, it really didn't accomplish the federal mandate at all of trying to deconcentrate the minority groups.
There were public housing units.
We're talking about families with numbers of children and something that there was no private housing which would meet their needs.
The public housing which was necessary for this often was four and five bedroom units typically within the complexes.
And some of these multi-bedroom units were constructed in complexes located in otherwise distant locations, elite neighborhoods, but lacking

walking distance to shopping, lacking good public transportation, and built in concentrations of sometimes as many as 600 units, which we began to multiply the units by the number of bedrooms, by the potential population.
There are complexes which easily you have over 1,500 people, all relocated from the same basic area.
which now becomes an enclave of poverty in otherwise a neighborhood that sees no relationship with it.
The social integration hasn't been accomplished because of this.

But what happened in south El Paso is that where the attitude had always been rather passive in terms of the role of the government as it affected their livelihood, an attitude of don't make waves, the militancy began to emerge among the neighborhood.
They had seen, through public policy, their neighborhood cut the population in half with the result of scattered vacant parcels all through the neighborhood.
They had not seen good and wise development come in to follow it.
Rather, sometimes the remnants of foundations left on there, it became just a
opportunity for other kinds of social problems of petty crime and gathering places for vagrants and such.

They knew of their family members who now were relocated to distant parts of the city and were living in far superior housing but were completely unhappy because of what had happened to their lifestyle and lifestyle pattern.
And it was in 1975 more or less that

at the instruction of John Cunningham, I worked with some of the staff in trying to once again prepare a study and a program of improvements for the area to try to address the problems of, particularly the ongoing problems of the continued magnitude of the substandard housing and concentration of the poor that exist in South El Paso.
And what we encountered was
considerable resistance from the neighborhood.
Suspicion that there was really a secret plan to remove all the residents, that we really wanted just to commercialize all of it.
We didn't care about their needs.
Contrary to federal mandates about social integration and relocating the poor to better class neighborhoods to encourage, as I said, social economic integration,

These people didn't want to leave, and they made that point as many times, that they were quite happy with the neighborhood that existed as it existed, and they wanted the housing problem addressed as it existed.
I think as a young intern working on my degree, I was down here and I was encountering the trenches of citizen participation for the first time.
Didn't find a very placid, meek population sitting down there and waiting until presentations were concluded to then politely ask questions.
I was working with small groups that were shaking their fist and walking out of meetings and making threats.
And people were quite unhappy.
And also, maybe I began to see some of the weakness of meetings per se as I
I began to encounter that there were different attitudes in the neighborhood.

There were some very militant youth groups that would make as though they represented all the people in the area, who in fact didn't, but they would lobby very effectively at public meetings that were held to make it seem as though the overall consensus of the neighborhood was in keeping with their particular notions of what should happen.
As I said, I was here on an internship.
I didn't see even that particular program to its completion.
I saw the different elements as they began to come together.
And later, when I worked with the planning staff again, the programs had different names and things of thinking.
The problems never really changed.
But it's taken a long way to come around to it was finally happening.

through a combination of perhaps less conservative thinking on the part of our local attorneys who had real great problems with any public money being spent to benefit a private citizen in the way of housing, rehabilitating housing.
Changes in the way of federal monies that became available through the Community Development Program.
Just changes of those that they seem,
of no great significance, but had great significance to us.
The funds that we had available for improving the neighborhood almost entirely were limited to doing the things that we did need to do.
Improving drainage and parks and putting more street lights and well that's all fine and good, but the problem was and always is and always was housing.
Terribly substandard housing.
Clearly the
what was necessary wasn't a continued wholesale destruction of a neighborhood and relocation of persons to distant parts of the city.

And finally, only in more recent times, a number of different programs come about where instead of tearing down units and building our monotonous public housing, we're making money available so that different organizations, be they private landlords, property owners that can go in and rehabilitate housing,
different nonprofit corporations made up of one notable organization I can think of is a group of ex-students from the local high school, the Bully exes, they call themselves.
How do you spell that?
Bully, as in Bully High School, named after Jim Bully, ironically.
I can tell you stories about Bully High School, too, and its social significance in the area, but I mean, as a group of persons,

an ex-students association composed of persons who grew up essentially in that neighborhood coming back and acquiring tenements and renovating them into standard units and then together with management contracts with public housing making them available at subsidized rates so they continue to be affordable for the people there.
Money that we've supplied to non-profit corporations which have created

They have built new housing and remodeled housing and then sell it on a, it becomes, rather than a condominium, it becomes a co-op of housing where you have an undivided interest in the whole complex.
We've been able to do, I think, more good in the area that way than anything else by not going in there and thinking we have to tear it all down and build it in a model of something that

in our middle class minds we see is the way a neighborhood should look but taking the resources that already exist, good stable brick buildings which have lasted for 50 years and taking them, remodeling them, making them into carving standard housing out of them and working with the programs that are available to keep them affordable for the people that would choose to remain in the area and
So that perhaps, in a sense, the complexion of the area hasn't changed.
Appearance-wise, things have not all of a sudden been drastically altered.
But what we've done is finally go in there and address the housing problem that really exists.
And it's a long road to hoe in it.
There's still many, many tenants down there that don't meet any codes that you could think of anywhere.
We're beginning to finally make a dent in it, though.

Like I say, it'll be many, many years before we can even think we've finally really come close to an end, but I think we're finally moving in the right direction, and maybe as an indicator of that, what I encountered in that neighborhood in the way of militancy and resistance is more or less gone away, and there's more of an attitude of trust and cooperation now as we finally have a housing program which is seen by all parties as being responsive to the neighborhood's needs.
Does the planning department have Spanish-speaking planners as liaison to that project?
Very definitely, very definitely.
In fact, I was one of the few people that was allowed down in the neighborhood that couldn't speak Spanish.
Something which, on a very different subject, we're talking about different categories of thinking that have planning significance in El Paso.
One element that's only beginning to unfold right now is a change of the attitude of the community regarding the mountains, which bisect the city.
These poor mountains have been ravaged for all kinds of crazy things from almost time immemorial.
People have had the craziest notions of building
giant clocks on top of them and roads right down the ridge line and one thing or another.
It wasn't a lot of attitude on the part of the city of really caring for the mountains.
All in all, the rough terrain of the mountains, it didn't allow for a lot of development.
It didn't allow for the properties to be developed economically.
And so outside of the high school's pain there,
their school initials on the mountains, and radio towers putting their transmitting towers on top of the mountain.
Not a lot happened on the mountains themselves, and they remained pretty much as they always had been.
Well, land development techniques change over time, and more recently the development of some very difficult terrain is becoming economically feasible.
People that would be inclined to do so
would provide a market for elite housing that offered a spectacular view by being built into the mountain itself.
And there's been a growing awareness on the part of the community that the mountain, almost every inch of it was privately owned and not protected from anything that could happen.
This led some years back to the acquisition
politicking on the part of the local legislators from the El Paso area to encourage the state to acquire much of this mountain and designate it as a wilderness park.
And this, in fact, is being done.
But there remains much mountainous terrain, particularly in the southernmost third of the mountain that lies within the very densely developed core of the city itself that
is still in private hands, that there is a growing development pressure for it.

And I find it noteworthy in the sense that through a lot of meetings and studies and the adoption of ordinances and now continuing changes to the ordinance, the city is beginning to try to do something which
can't be readily borrowed from just any city anywhere.
And that's to define if the mountain areas are developed, how should they be developed?
How can we preserve the character of the mountain yet still allow the terrain to be developed?
The city has never, they've only recently incorporated site plan review as a condition of billing permit as part of their
of certain zoning classifications.
We have to go.
Come on.

In any case, some planning thinking is having to be put to focus on a problem which is rather unique to communities such as El Paso that do have mountains terrain that is intended and can be developed.
And it's created a new challenge for some of the planning staff which was accustomed to studying plans on two-dimensional maps to have to begin to think three-dimensionally.
So many of the physical implications of development patterns and what that does to the aesthetics and livability and all the other physical implications that go along with
Drainage patterns and traffic patterns are beginning to have to be looked at quite closely.
General principles can be identified, but the specific standards have been very elusive.
The staff is only now beginning to come up with some workable solutions.
It's not something which I can point to in the city and say, look at what has been accomplished.
I'd rather only highlight that as something that
is ongoing right now.
And I don't have a lot of good examples of ordinances and policies which have been adopted.
I can show you maybe some of the bad examples and mistakes that have been made.
But I think it's interesting from a planning perspective only in that it is a relatively unique situation that the kind of planning I think is best, a very localized

an individual kind of solution has to be sought so that you apply not the standards that you get out of national publications, but the principles that govern planning to bring them to bear on a unique and very community-oriented problem.
We've already mentioned Kessler and Cunningham.
Are there any other major personalities that have affected planning in El Paso?
Mayors or

planners themselves private groups I can't really give you a chronology of the different personalities that have been involved in the directorship itself outside of the more recent period when I knew John Cunningham and interim director Bill Adams and now current director Nestor Valencia there have been
Have there been any private citizen groups that have been influential in supporting planning?
El Paso remains a city that community groups, neighborhood organizations and such, they spring up usually on an issue-oriented basis.
They have one particular axe to grind, and all too often they disappear once that issue, the immediate crisis, is passed.

And I think there would have been, there would be a lot more interesting examples of good planning had there been the pressure from the community and the neighborhood organizations on an ongoing basis that unfortunately has been lacking all too often.
No continuity.
Not really, not really.
That continuity, the lack of continuity of leadership within the community itself rather than of elected, of city officials themselves.
is perhaps something that's held back plenty.
Although you have had a series of mayors who have been very supportive of planning.
Yes, on occasion we've had mayors, some very conservative, who had the attitude that federal money was tainted with tainted money and should be avoided at all costs.

The most important thing was to hold down taxes and never pass a tax approval, and consequently there were very few in the way of capital improvements done either through locally generated revenue or through program monies available through the federal government.
There have been other mayors who took a more active role.
Mayor Judson Williams comes to mind as a person who was really interested in seeing some of the
elements of the city progress in terms of planning and thinking.
I believe he was the mayor during the period of the Chamazal Treaty being hashed out.
All too often, though, I think the, like I said, it's a parochial and rather conservative city, and so there's not been a lot of, the citizens themselves don't

give a strong mandate to the elected leaders to pursue different planning goals and consequently the leadership hasn't hasn't pushed new planning directions frontiers taking a look at the future what do you think are the major problems that el paso planning is going to have to address water usage water it has to be one of the most critical issues in the city
We've covered that in other interviews.
Any other issues?
I would think one thing that has to be faced up to is the changing complexion of the city from an economic standpoint that has rather negative implications into the future.
The city is becoming increasingly a manufacturing center.
And increasingly, the white collar staff, the headquarters operations are disappearing.
There's a real danger that the city can become one dimensional in the future in the sense of having too many industries that employ apparel industries, for instance, that employ people that

need no more training than necessary to sew zippers on blue jeans and too little of the management staff in the future this may create in essence a leadership vacuum as the persons with the greatest incomes are the plant managers for the large national companies who owe no local allegiance to the community are here only as a stepping stone to other positions and to
And then, of course, your problems with Mexico and the two economies rubbing shoulders every day.

It's been one thing that has been very successful in this area, the Maquiladora program, the twin plants that enable industry in Mexico to work with industry in the United States to do parcel assembly of
items, electronic components, and such, that later then are shipped into the US for export.
Different tariff laws and things like that that are changed to allow for this.

It's created giant industrial parks on the Mexican side that have improved the standard of living in lettuce in particular, and have created their counterpart development in the United States, in El Paso in particular.
We see some of the final assembly.
We see, of course, a lot of warehousing and such.
That, in a sense, is rather positive.

It is provided, although it is creating other population pressures by virtue of continued immigration of some of the rural area Mexicans to the urban area around Juarez with hope of getting their slice of the economic pie, which never grows as fast as the population seems to.
Any other basic issues that are going to have to be faced by clients?

I think El Paso, like many cities, we're finally beginning to see a slowing down of the peripheral fringe of the community and a reawakening of the value of some of the built up areas of the community.
and the real public concern over some of the old neighborhoods with their Corinthian column decorated homes that are being destroyed.
And it's a challenge from a planning perspective of how to redevelop and how to renew and how to restore some of the quality of life in the built-up area of the city
has just a totally different social makeup than when it was originally created.
It's not as easy to point out areas in El Paso where you find the so-called gentrification.

You find more areas that the homes have been subdivided into, grand old homes have been subdivided into five apartments, and the complexion of the neighborhood now is entirely a Hispanic community of very modest economic means, and it's beset with problems of
crime and the air pollution which hangs over the city, yet there's a physical resource there which is being lost.
And there's a genuine community concern over trying to salvage that.
And you've got to realize the economics and social fabric that exists there now and see how that can best be integrated with the physical resource which does exist.
That would be a planning challenge now and into the future.
Ed, thanks very much.
If you can think of anything to add to this when we get the transcription to you, feel free to add or delete.
Thank you very much.
